  <span id="freeText11097931815299328547" style="display:none">This book's biggest strength is its sense of place. Robinson develops settings so well—all the way from state down to city, home, and the internal monologue of our narrator, Ruth. It's a very atmospheric novel that swept me away. However, I found the story to be a bit lacking. The novel ponders themes of isolation, home life, transience and familial relationships, but doesn't necessarily deliver a strong verdict on any of these things. That's ok; I don't expect to be hit over the head with what I should be thinking, especially while reading fiction. But Ruth is so naive and self-conscious and unsure of everything in life, which makes her a great observer but a rather dull narrator. Her Aunt Sylvie was far more fascinating, and I almost wish we had read from her perspective, or switched to hers halfway through. <b>3.5 stars.</b></span>
